<zyHTML id="09303d87-ee16-e8a5-5330-4fbd7ec6fd55" subsection="true" caption="Strings and string literals">
<h3>Strings and string literals</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyHTML id="ecd58478-e177-427e-b1a8-ecc0f6802c35">
<p> <zyDefn>A _string_ is a sequence of characters</zyDefn>. <zyDefn> A _string literal_ surrounds a character sequence with double quotes, as in "Hello", "52 Main St.", or "42"</zyDefn>, vs. an integer literal like 42 or character literal like 'a'. Various characters may be in a string, such as letters, numbers, spaces, or symbols like $ or %, as in "$100 for Julia!!". Earlier sections showed string literals being output, as in: 
<zyVersion version="java"><zyICode>System.out.print("Hello");</zyICode>.</zyVersion>
</p> 
</zyHTML>



<zyTool name="strToCharSeq" id="230f9254-4cb6-1d5d-a249-6b58351d827b" caption="A string is stored as a sequence of characters in memory.">
<zyInstructions>Type a string to see how a string is stored as a sequence of characters in memory. In this case, the string happens to be in memory locations 501 to 506. Try typing Hello! or 627.</zyInstructions>
<zyAltDescription>
This activity demonstrates how a string is stored as a sequence of characters in memory. Say a string up to 6 characters happens to be allocated to memory locations 501 to 506. If the string is  "Julia", 'J' would be stored in memory location 501, 'u' in 502, 'l' in 503, 'i' in 504, and 'a' in 505, leaving memory location 506 empty.
</zyAltDescription>
</zyTool>



