<zyHTML id="6141843e-96ee-8729-2152-ddbd214548ae" subsection="true" caption="Example: Word game">
<h3>Example: Word game</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyHTML id="9931cfc8-4059-7a3d-5f5c-8592b434a71e" caption="">
<p>The following example illustrates getting strings from input and putting strings to output. </p>
</zyHTML>



<zyVersion version="java">
<zyFigure caption="Strings example: Word game." id="8d54cf13-31ca-bcd2-be9d-c9878ba3e87a" type="CodeConsole">
<zyCode language="java"> 
import java.util.Scanner;

/* A game inspired by "Mad Libs" where user enters nouns,
   verbs, etc., and then a story using those words is output.
*/

public class StoryGame {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
      String wordRelative;
      String wordFood;
      String wordAdjective;
      String wordTimePeriod;

      // Get user's words
      System.out.println("Provide input without spaces.");

      System.out.println("Enter a kind of relative: ");
      wordRelative = scnr.next();

      System.out.println("Enter a kind of food: ");
      wordFood = scnr.next();

      System.out.println("Enter an adjective: ");
      wordAdjective = scnr.next();

      System.out.println("Enter a time period: ");
      wordTimePeriod = scnr.next();

      // Tell the story
      System.out.println();
      System.out.print  ("My " + wordRelative);
      System.out.println(" says eating " + wordFood);
      System.out.println("will make me more " + wordAdjective + ",");
      System.out.println("so now I eat it every " + wordTimePeriod + ".");
   }
}
</zyCode>
<zyConsole>
Provide input without spaces.
Enter a kind of relative: 
mother
Enter a kind of food: 
apples
Enter an adjective: 
loud
Enter a time period: 
week

My mother says eating apples
will make me more loud,
so now I eat it every week.
</zyConsole>
</zyFigure>
</zyVersion>



<zyHTML id="c6fb7441-0736-6945-c284-a8724b59d4b2" subsection="true" caption="Getting a string with whitespace from input">
<h3>Getting a string with whitespace from input</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyHTML id="4ebc729d-d267-3336-60db-5540b2c761a6" caption="">
<p>Sometimes a programmer wishes to get whitespace characters into a string, such as getting a user's input of the name "Franklin D. Roosevelt" into a string variable presidentName.  </p>
</zyHTML>



<zyVersion version="java">
<zyHTML id="4908757f-fee9-4112-a724-b1586d6431d9">
<p>For such cases, the language supports getting an entire line into a string. <zyDefn>The method _scnr.nextLine()_ gets all remaining text on the current input line, up to the next newline character (which is removed from input but not put in stringVar).</zyDefn> </p> 
</zyHTML>
</zyVersion>



<zyVersion version="java">
<zyQSetMultipleChoice caption="Getting a string with whitespace from input" id="db57b5b7-7ca1-4e56-bfec-8ce1fdb02a3f">
<p>What does the following statement store<!--get--> into the indicated variable, for the given input? <br />
<zyCode language="java" nobox="true">firstString = scnr.nextLine();
secondString = scnr.nextLine();</zyCode>
</zyVersion>
</p>

<zyQ>
<zyQText>Hello there!<br />
Welcome.<br />
<br />
firstString gets _____ . 
</zyQText>
<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>Hello</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement gets the entire line, not stopping at the first whitespace. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice correct="true">
<zyQAns>Hello there!</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement gets the entire first line. The string does not contain the newline, which instead is just disposed. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>Hello there! Welcome.</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement only gets the first line, and does not also get the second line. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText>I<br />
don't<br />
know.<br />
<br />
firstString gets _____ .</zyQText>
<zyQChoice correct="true">
<zyQAns>I</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first line consists of just one letter, so firstString will just have that one letter. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>I don't</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The statement stops after the first line, and does not get the second line also. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>I<br />
don't</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The statement does not get two lines and the newline, but stops at the end of the first line.</zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText>Hey buddy. <br />
What's up?<br />
<br />
secondString gets _____ .</zyQText>
<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>Hey buddy.</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement gets the first line, so firstString gets "Hey buddy", not secondString. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice correct="true">
<zyQAns>What's up?</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement gets the first line, "Hey buddy." The second statement gets "What's up?" into secondString.</zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>(empty)</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The second statement doesn't get a blank line. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText><br />
abc<br />
def<br />
<br />
secondString gets _____ . (Note that the first line above is blank). </zyQText>
<zyQChoice correct="true">
<zyQAns>abc</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement gets the first line, which is blank, yielding an empty string. Thus the second statement gets "abc" into secondString. This behavior is quite different than the approach for getting a string without whitespace, which ignores leading whitespace and thus would have ignored the initial blank line. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>def</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The first statement gets the first line, which happens to be blank. Thus, the second statement will get the second line, which is not def. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>(blank)</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The second statement doesn't get a blank line. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>
</zyQ>

<zyQ>
<zyQText>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Walk away<br />
<br />
firstString gets _____ . (Note the leading spaces before Walk). </zyQText>
<zyQChoice>
<zyQAns>Walk away</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>That string has no leading spaces. The statement does not ignore leading spaces. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>

<zyQChoice correct="true">
<zyQAns>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Walk away</zyQAns>
<zyQExpl>The statement gets the entire line, including leading spaces. The statements do not ignore leading spaces. </zyQExpl>
</zyQChoice>
</zyQ>
</zyQSetMultipleChoice>
</zyVersion>



<zyHTML id="dc431a3d-a1b1-aac6-7b84-ccf8c200d4ae" subsection="true" caption="Example: Getting multi-word names">
<h3>Example: Getting multi-word names</h3>
</zyHTML>


<zyVersion version="java">
<zyFigure caption="Reading an input string containing spaces using nextLine." id="c39c6dad-8e8b-65ac-8a44-338795d1ac7b"  type="CodeConsole">
<zyCode language="java"> 
import java.util.Scanner;

public class NameWelcome {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
      String firstName;
      String lastName;

      System.out.println("Enter first name: ");
      firstName = scnr.nextLine(); // Gets entire line up to ENTER

      System.out.println("Enter last name: ");
